%[text] # A05: Molecular Property Prediction Using Neural Networks
%[text] EasyMolKit Analytics  -- Layer 3
%[text] QSAR (Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationship) modeling has traditionally relied on linear regression: fast, interpretable, and effective when the descriptor-property relationship is approximately linear.
%[text] Neural networks offer a more flexible alternative, automatically capturing nonlinear interactions among descriptors. The trade-off is that they require more data and are prone to overfitting on the small datasets typical of drug discovery.
%[text] In this exercise, we build a small feedforward network to predict ALogP from 8 structural descriptors of FDA-approved drugs, then compare it directly with the linear regression model from A03.
%[text] ### What You Will Learn in This Tutorial
%[text] - Understand why small QSAR datasets are challenging for neural networks
%[text] - Build and train a feedforward regression network using trainnet()
%[text] - Reduce overfitting with dropout and learning rate schedules
%[text] - Interpret learning curves: convergence, overfitting, underfitting
%[text] - Understand when to choose simpler linear models over neural networks \
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Recommended: A03 (QSAR Regression) for context on the same dataset
%[text] - Deep Learning Toolbox (trainnet, trainingOptions, fullyConnectedLayer)
%[text] - No internet connection required
%[text] - Estimated time required: 35-50 minutes
%[text] - How to run: Execute sections one by one with Ctrl+Enter \
%[text] ### Data: 
%[text] - data/list/fda\_drugs.csv  -- 200 FDA-approved drugs (ChEMBL, CC-BY-SA 3.0).
%[text] - The ALogP column is used as the regression target for the Crippen-Wildman lipophilicity estimate. \
%[text] ### References
%[text] - Srivastava N, Hinton G, Krizhevsky A, Sutskever I, Salakhutdinov R (2014) Dropout: a simple way to prevent neural networks from overfitting. *J Mach Learn Res* 15:1929-1958.
%[text] - Kingma D & Ba J (2015) Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization. arXiv:1412.6980.
%[text] - Ramsundar B et al. (2015) Massively multitask networks for drug discovery. arXiv:1502.02072.
%[text] - Tropsha A (2010) Best practices for QSAR model development, validation, and exploitation. *Mol Inform* 29:476-488. doi:10.1002/minf.201000061. \
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:4821b3cc]
%[text] Warm up Python/RDKit process before main execution.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
logSection("A05", "Section 0: Setup", "Analytics L3"); %[output:046c11d5]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Loading FDA-approved drugs and calculating descriptors
%[text] We compute the same 8 descriptors as A03 so this tutorial runs fully self-contained.
%[text] ### Descriptor Matrix Layout
%[text] The 8 descriptors -- MolWt, TPSA, NumHDonors, NumHAcceptors, NumRotatableBonds, RingCount, FractionCSP3, and HeavyAtomCount -- collectively quantify size, polarity, shape, and topology. They form the feature matrix $X$ (rows = molecules, columns = descriptors), paired with the target vector $y$ (ALogP).
logSection("A05", "Section 1: Loading FDA-approved drugs and calculating descriptors", "Analytics L3"); %[output:7d39abe3]
DATA_FILE  = "data/list/fda_drugs.csv";
FEAT_NAMES = ["MolWt", "TPSA", "NumHDonors", "NumHAcceptors", ...
              "NumRotatableBonds", "RingCount", "FractionCSP3", "HeavyAtomCount"];
N_FEATS    = numel(FEAT_NAMES);
rawTbl = readtable(DATA_FILE, TextType="string");
logInfo("Loaded %d rows from %s", height(rawTbl), DATA_FILE); %[output:2d0cbe14]
if isnumeric(rawTbl.ALogP)
    alogpVec = rawTbl.ALogP;
else
    alogpVec = str2double(rawTbl.ALogP);
end
nRaw  = height(rawTbl);
X_all = nan(nRaw, N_FEATS);
y_all = nan(nRaw, 1);
valid = false(nRaw, 1);
for k = 1:nRaw
    if isnan(alogpVec(k)), continue; end
    try
        mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(rawTbl.SMILES(k));
        s   = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol, FEAT_NAMES);
        row = zeros(1, N_FEATS);
        for d = 1:N_FEATS
            row(d) = s.(FEAT_NAMES(d));
        end
        X_all(k, :) = row;
        y_all(k)    = alogpVec(k);
        valid(k)    = true;
    catch ME
        logWarn("Skipping %s: %s", rawTbl.Name(k), ME.message);
    end
end
logInfo("Completed descriptor calculation for %d entries", sum(valid)); %[output:6b21b1fd]
X        = X_all(valid, :);
y        = y_all(valid);
molNames = rawTbl.Name(valid);
nMols    = sum(valid);
logInfo("Dataset: %d / %d molecules (ALogP range: %.2f to %.2f)", ... %[output:group:5403c291] %[output:496722a6]
    nMols, nRaw, min(y), max(y)); %[output:group:5403c291] %[output:496722a6]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Exploring ALogP Distribution
%[text] Before building any model, we examine the distribution of the target variable ALogP. Knowing the shape and outlier structure now helps interpret training behavior later.
%[text] ### Why Check the Target Distribution Before Training
%[text] Neural network regressors minimize Mean Squared Error (MSE): $\\frac{1}{n} \\sum (\\hat{y}(i) - y(i))^2$, where $\\hat{y}(i)$ is the prediction for molecule $i$, $y(i)$ the observed value, and $n$ the number of molecules.
%[text] MSE penalizes large errors quadratically, so outliers in $y$ can disproportionately affect the learned weights.
%[text] The network may attempt to reduce errors for a few extreme values at the expense of prediction accuracy for the majority of molecules.
%[text] Visualizing the target distribution before learning can help determine if transformations (such as clipping or winsorization) are needed to mitigate the impact of outliers.
%[text] In this exercise, we will use the raw ALogP as is.
logSection("A05", "Section 2: Exploring ALogP Distribution", "Analytics L3"); %[output:8d5d9009]
figure("Name", "A05 ALogP Distribution"); %[output:040936c0]
histogram(y, 20, FaceColor=[0.2 0.6 0.8]); %[output:040936c0]
xlabel("ALogP"); ylabel("Count"); %[output:040936c0]
title("ALogP Distribution -- FDA Approved Drugs"); %[output:040936c0]
xline(mean(y),   "r--", sprintf("Mean=%.2f",   mean(y)),   LabelHorizontalAlignment="right",  LabelOrientation="horizontal"); %[output:040936c0]
xline(median(y), "g--", sprintf("Median=%.2f", median(y)), LabelHorizontalAlignment="left",   LabelOrientation="horizontal"); %[output:040936c0]
grid on; %[output:040936c0]
logInfo("ALogP: Mean=%.2f, Standard Deviation=%.2f, Skewness=%.2f", mean(y), std(y), skewness(y)); %[output:4a999f35]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Training / Validation / Test Split and Feature Standardization
%[text] With the target distribution examined, we now create the three-way split that neural network training requires. The validation set monitors overfitting in real time; the test set provides the final unbiased evaluation.
%[text] ### Three-way Split for Neural Network Training
%[text] Unlike the k-fold cross-validation used in A03, neural networks require a dedicated validation set.
%[text] There are three reasons why a validation set is needed: (a) to monitor overfitting in real-time, (b) to trigger early stopping (a mechanism to stop training when the validation loss no longer improves), and (c) to tune hyperparameters without contaminating the test set.
%[text] In this exercise, we will split the data in a 70% training / 15% validation / 15% test ratio. For 200 molecules, this results in approximately 140 / 30 / 30.
%[text] The statistics for standardization (scaling) such as mean and standard deviation are calculated using only the training data and applied to the validation and test sets. Using information from outside the training set for standardization can cause "data leakage" and lead to overly optimistic evaluations.
logSection("A05", "Section 3: Training / Validation / Test Split and Feature Standardization", "Analytics L3"); %[output:9ff5d7d0]
MINI_BATCH_SIZE = 32;
VAL_FREQUENCY   = 5;   % validate every 5 training iterations
rng(42);  % fix random seed for reproducibility
cv1    = cvpartition(nMols, "HoldOut", 0.30);
trIdx  = training(cv1);
tmpIdx = test(cv1);
Xtmp = X(tmpIdx, :);
ytmp = y(tmpIdx);
cv2     = cvpartition(sum(tmpIdx), "HoldOut", 0.50);
valIdx  = training(cv2);
tstIdx  = test(cv2);
Xtr  = X(trIdx,  :);  ytr  = y(trIdx);
Xval = Xtmp(valIdx,:); yval = ytmp(valIdx);
Xte  = Xtmp(tstIdx,:); yte  = ytmp(tstIdx);
%[text] Standardize features using only the statistics from the training set.
Xmean = mean(Xtr, 1);
Xstd  = std(Xtr,  0, 1);
Xstd(Xstd < 1e-12) = 1;  % guard: avoid /0 for constant descriptors
Xtr_s  = (Xtr  - Xmean) ./ Xstd;
Xval_s = (Xval - Xmean) ./ Xstd;
Xte_s  = (Xte  - Xmean) ./ Xstd;
logInfo("Split: Training=%d / Validation=%d / Test=%d (Total=%d)", ... %[output:group:42ab9914] %[output:3b85ac02]
    size(Xtr, 1), size(Xval, 1), size(Xte, 1), nMols); %[output:group:42ab9914] %[output:3b85ac02]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Definition of Neural Network Architecture
%[text] With the data split and standardized, we design the network architecture. For a small dataset like this, a shallow 2-hidden-layer network with dropout regularization strikes a practical balance between capacity and generalization.
%[text] ### Design of Feedforward Network for Small Dataset Regression
%[text] The network takes 8 standardized descriptors as input, processes them through 2 hidden layers, and outputs a single ALogP prediction $\\hat{y}$.
%[text] The layer-by-layer transformations are: (1) first hidden layer $h\_1 = \\max(0, W\_1 x + b\_1)$ (ReLU) followed by dropout at $p = 0.20$; (2) second hidden layer $h\_2 = \\max(0, W\_2 h\_1 + b\_2)$; (3) linear output $\\hat{y} = W\_3 h\_2 + b\_3$.
%[text] ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit) is an activation function defined as $\\max(0, x)$, which is computationally efficient and avoids the vanishing gradient problem (where gradients disappear in deep layers, halting learning).
%[text] Dropout (p=0.20) is a regularization technique that randomly sets 20% of neurons to zero in each training forward pass, preventing dependency (co-adaptation) on specific neurons.
%[text] With about 140 training molecules and 2689 training parameters, the parameter-to-sample ratio is approximately 19, making dropout essential to prevent overfitting.
logSection("A05", "Section 4: Definition of Neural Network Architecture", "Analytics L3"); %[output:271cf614]
layers = [
    featureInputLayer(N_FEATS, Normalization="none")
    fullyConnectedLayer(64)
    reluLayer
    dropoutLayer(0.20)
    fullyConnectedLayer(32)
    reluLayer
    fullyConnectedLayer(1)];
net = dlnetwork(layers);
%[text] Count the number of trainable parameters.
numParams = 0;
for k = 1:height(net.Learnables)
    numParams = numParams + numel(extractdata(net.Learnables.Value{k}));
end
logInfo("Architecture: FC(64)-ReLU-Drop(0.2)-FC(32)-ReLU-FC(1)"); %[output:08ef991d]
logInfo("Trainable parameters: %d  (Parameter/sample ratio = %.1f)", ... %[output:group:5f6c5c89] %[output:33e60031]
    numParams, numParams / size(Xtr_s, 1)); %[output:group:5f6c5c89] %[output:33e60031]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Network Training
%[text] With the architecture defined, we now train the network. Monitor the progress window to track training loss and validation loss -- divergence between them signals overfitting.
%[text] ### Adam Optimizer and Piecewise Learning Rate Schedule
%[text] Adam (Adaptive Moment Estimation) is an optimizer that adaptively adjusts the learning rate for each parameter using the exponentially decaying average of past gradients.
%[text] In the piecewise schedule, the learning rate is halved at epoch 80: use a learning rate of $1 \\times 10^{-3}$ for epochs 1-80, and $5 \\times 10^{-4}$ for epochs 81-200.
%[text] In mini-batch SGD, a random subset of 32 molecules is used for each Adam step. When processing 140 training molecules with MiniBatchSize=32, one epoch consists of 4 iterations.
logSection("A05", "Section 5: Network Training", "Analytics L3"); %[output:4349c1a3]
opts = trainingOptions("adam", ...
    MaxEpochs=200, ...
    MiniBatchSize=MINI_BATCH_SIZE, ...
    InitialLearnRate=1e-3, ...
    LearnRateSchedule="piecewise", ...
    LearnRateDropFactor=0.5, ...
    LearnRateDropPeriod=80, ...
    ValidationData={Xval_s, yval}, ...
    ValidationFrequency=VAL_FREQUENCY, ...
    Plots="training-progress", ...
    Verbose=false);
logInfo("Training for 200 epochs (approximately 30-60 seconds)..."); %[output:9f2ee432]
[net, trainInfo] = trainnet(Xtr_s, ytr, net, "mse", opts); %[output:24eade4c]
%[text] Due to differences in MATLAB versions, the structure of trainInfo varies, so the method to extract loss values is switched for each version.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Version | Structure of trainInfo |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | R2024a | TrainingLoss / ValidationLoss (stored directly as arrays) |
%[text] | R2025b | TrainingHistory.Loss / ValidationHistory.Loss (column "Loss" in tables) |
%[text] | R2025a | TrainingHistory table with TrainingLoss and ValidationLoss columns |
%[text:table]
try
    % R2024a style: direct array fields
    trLossAll   = double(trainInfo.TrainingLoss);
    valLossAll  = double(trainInfo.ValidationLoss);
    valIterNums = [];
catch
    try
        % R2025b style: separate TrainingHistory / ValidationHistory tables, column "Loss"
        trLossAll   = double(trainInfo.TrainingHistory.Loss);
        valLossAll  = double(trainInfo.ValidationHistory.Loss);
        valIterNums = double(trainInfo.ValidationHistory.Iteration);
    catch
        % R2025a style: single TrainingHistory table with TrainingLoss/ValidationLoss columns
        h           = trainInfo.TrainingHistory;
        trLossAll   = double(h.TrainingLoss);
        valMask     = ~isnan(h.ValidationLoss);
        valLossAll  = double(h.ValidationLoss(valMask));
        valIterNums = [];
    end
end
finalValLoss = valLossAll(end);
logInfo("Training complete. Final validation MSE=%.4f (RMSE=%.3f)", ... %[output:group:04af713d] %[output:6275e141]
    finalValLoss, sqrt(max(finalValLoss, 0))); %[output:group:04af713d] %[output:6275e141]
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Learning Curve Analysis
%[text] With training complete, we analyze the learning curve to diagnose model behavior. The gap between training and validation loss is the primary indicator of overfitting.
%[text] ### How to Read Learning Curves
%[text] Learning curves plot the change in loss over epochs (the number of times the entire training data is passed through).
%[text] **Good Fit**: Both training loss and validation loss decrease and converge to similar values.
%[text] **Overfitting**: Training loss continues to decrease, but validation loss remains flat or increases.
%[text] **Underfitting**: Both losses remain high, indicating the model has not learned sufficiently.
logSection("A05", "Section 6: Learning Curve Analysis", "Analytics L3"); %[output:70d9d646]
% Calculate itersPerEpoch from actual training history (accurate with formula comparison)
nIterTotal    = numel(trLossAll);
nValPoints    = numel(valLossAll);
if isprop(trainInfo, 'TrainingHistory') && ismember('Epoch', trainInfo.TrainingHistory.Properties.VariableNames)
    itersPerEpoch = max(1, round(nIterTotal / max(trainInfo.TrainingHistory.Epoch)));
else
    itersPerEpoch = max(1, ceil(size(Xtr_s, 1) / MINI_BATCH_SIZE));
end
epochsTr  = (1:nIterTotal) / itersPerEpoch;
if ~isempty(valIterNums)
    epochsVal = valIterNums / itersPerEpoch;
else
    epochsVal = (1:nValPoints) * VAL_FREQUENCY / itersPerEpoch;
end
%[text] To make interpretation easier, convert MSE to RMSE (same unit as ALogP).
trRmse  = sqrt(max(trLossAll,  0));
valRmse = sqrt(max(valLossAll, 0));
%[text] Smooth the learning curve using a moving average with a window of 1 epoch.
winLen    = max(1, itersPerEpoch);
trSmoothed = movmean(trRmse, winLen, "Endpoints", "fill");
figure("Name", "A05 Learning Curve"); %[output:5cd343c7]
plot(epochsTr,  trRmse,    "Color", [0.7 0.8 1.0], LineWidth=0.8, ... %[output:5cd343c7]
    DisplayName="Training (Raw)"); hold on; %[output:5cd343c7]
plot(epochsTr,  trSmoothed, "b-", LineWidth=2.0, DisplayName="Training (Smoothed)"); %[output:5cd343c7]
plot(epochsVal, valRmse,    "r--", LineWidth=2.0, DisplayName="Validation"); %[output:5cd343c7]
xlabel("Epoch"); ylabel("RMSE (ALogP Unit)"); %[output:5cd343c7]
title("A05: Learning Curve"); %[output:5cd343c7]
legend(Location="northeast"); %[output:5cd343c7]
grid on; %[output:5cd343c7]
%[text] Mark the best validation epoch with a vertical line.
[minValRmse, minValIdx] = min(valRmse);
xline(epochsVal(minValIdx), "--k", ... %[output:group:6e81729a] %[output:5cd343c7]
    sprintf("Best Validation RMSE=%.3f (Epoch %.0f)", minValRmse, epochsVal(minValIdx)), ... %[output:5cd343c7]
    LabelHorizontalAlignment="left", LabelVerticalAlignment="bottom", ... %[output:5cd343c7]
    LabelOrientation="horizontal", HandleVisibility="off"); %[output:group:6e81729a] %[output:5cd343c7]
logInfo("Best Validation RMSE=%.3f (Epoch %.0f)", minValRmse, epochsVal(minValIdx)); %[output:4f362907]
%%
%[text] ## Section 7: Test Set Evaluation
%[text] With the learning curve analyzed, we evaluate the model on the held-out test set for the first and only time. This result is the final, unbiased performance estimate.
%[text] ### One-time Test Set Evaluation
%[text] The test set is evaluated exactly once after all design decisions (architecture and hyperparameters) have been finalized.
%[text] The main evaluation metrics are as follows: $R^2 = 1 - \\frac{\\sum (y(i) - \\hat{y}(i))^2}{\\sum (y(i) - \\bar{y})^2}$ (closer to 1 is better), RMSE (error measured in the same units as $y$), and MAE (an error metric robust to outliers).
%[text] In the scatter plot of actual vs predicted values, the closer the points are to the $y = x$ diagonal, the higher the prediction accuracy.
logSection("A05", "Section 7: Test Set Evaluation", "Analytics L3"); %[output:5145f22d]
yPred = double(predict(net, Xte_s));   % (nTest x 1) predicted ALogP
res   = yte - yPred;
rmse  = sqrt(mean(res.^2));
mae   = mean(abs(res));
r2    = 1 - sum(res.^2) / sum((yte - mean(yte)).^2);
logInfo("Test Set: R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f  MAE=%.3f  (n=%d)", r2, rmse, mae, numel(yte)); %[output:49568982]
figure("Name", "A05 Test Predictions"); %[output:1df16c09]
tiledlayout(1, 2); %[output:1df16c09]
nexttile; %[output:1df16c09]
scatter(yte, yPred, 50, "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.7, ... %[output:1df16c09]
    MarkerFaceColor=[0.2 0.5 0.9]); %[output:1df16c09]
hold on; %[output:1df16c09]
lim = [min([yte; yPred]) - 0.5, max([yte; yPred]) + 0.5];
plot(lim, lim, "k--", LineWidth=1.5); %[output:1df16c09]
xlabel("Actual ALogP"); ylabel("Predicted ALogP"); %[output:1df16c09]
title(sprintf("Actual vs Predicted  (R^2=%.3f)", r2)); %[output:1df16c09]
grid on; %[output:1df16c09]
nexttile; %[output:1df16c09]
histogram(res, 15, FaceColor=[0.9 0.4 0.3]); %[output:1df16c09]
xline(0, "--k", LineWidth=1.5); %[output:1df16c09]
xlabel("Residuals (Actual - Predicted)"); ylabel("Count"); %[output:1df16c09]
title(sprintf("Residuals  (RMSE=%.3f, MAE=%.3f)", rmse, mae)); %[output:1df16c09]
grid on; %[output:1df16c09]
%%
%[text] ## Section 8: Linear Baseline Comparison and Discussion
%[text] With the neural network evaluated, we compare it against linear regression on the same training-test split.
%[text] Notice the important QSAR lesson here: more complex models are not always better.
%[text] ### Occam's Razor  -- Choose the simplest and most appropriate model
%[text] In QSAR, the "simplest and most appropriate model" is usually linear regression.
%[text] Replacing it with a neural network is limited to cases where (a) the data per descriptor is large with $N \> 1000$, (b) there is theoretical justification for expecting non-linearity, or (c) the performance of a cross-validated neural network significantly exceeds that of linear regression.
%[text] In drug datasets of 100-300 molecules, linear regression, random forest, and Gaussian process models usually match or exceed neural networks.
%[text] Graph Neural Networks (GNN) are where deep learning truly shines in cheminformatics.
%[text] For a fair comparison, we use the same training-test split created in Section 3.
logSection("A05", "Section 8: Linear Baseline Comparison and Discussion", "Analytics L3"); %[output:924dd1fd]
ftTbl    = array2table(Xtr_s, VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
ftTbl.ALogP = ytr;
lmMdl    = fitlm(ftTbl, "ALogP ~ " + strjoin(FEAT_NAMES, " + "));
teTbl    = array2table(Xte_s, VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
yLinPred = predict(lmMdl, teTbl);
r2Lin    = 1 - sum((yte - yLinPred).^2) / sum((yte - mean(yte)).^2);
rmseLin  = sqrt(mean((yte - yLinPred).^2));
maeLin   = mean(abs(yte - yLinPred));
logInfo("Linear Regression: R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f  MAE=%.3f", r2Lin, rmseLin, maeLin); %[output:4985d2f4]
logInfo("Neural Network:    R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f  MAE=%.3f", r2, rmse, mae); %[output:950cc062]
logInfo("NN Superiority:    dR2=%.3f  dRMSE=%+.3f  dMAE=%+.3f", ... %[output:group:84494c6b] %[output:42601cf9]
    r2 - r2Lin, rmseLin - rmse, maeLin - mae); %[output:group:84494c6b] %[output:42601cf9]
%[text] We compare the two models using three metrics.
figure("Name", "A05 Model Comparison"); %[output:3406fe90]
set(gcf, "Position", [100 100 1100 400]); %[output:3406fe90]
tiledlayout(1, 3); %[output:3406fe90]
metrics  = [r2Lin, r2; rmseLin, rmse; maeLin, mae];
ylabels  = ["R^2 (higher is better)", "RMSE (lower is better)", "MAE (lower is better)"];
for m = 1:3
    nexttile; %[output:3406fe90]
    bar(metrics(m, :), FaceColor="flat", CData=[0.4 0.6 0.9; 0.9 0.4 0.3]);
    set(gca, "XTickLabel", ["Linear", "Neural Network"]);
    ylabel(ylabels(m)); title(ylabels(m)); grid on;
    ylim([0, max(metrics(m, :)) * 1.3]);
end
sgtitle("A05: Linear Regression vs Neural Network (Same Training-Test Split)"); %[output:3406fe90]
%%
%[text] ## Summary
%[text] This exercise walked through the complete neural network workflow -- architecture design, training, learning curve diagnosis, and test set evaluation -- applied to ALogP prediction for 200 FDA-approved drugs.
%[text] - **Three-way split** (Training 70% / Validation 15% / Test 15%) allows for monitoring overfitting and fair final evaluation.
%[text] - **Standardization rule**: Scaling statistics should be calculated only from training data; using data outside of training can cause data leakage.
%[text] - **Adam optimizer** adaptively adjusts the learning rate for each parameter, achieving stable convergence when combined with a piecewise schedule.
%[text] - Dropout (p=0.20) randomly zeros 20% of neurons, a regularization technique to prevent overfitting in small-scale data.
%[text] - By observing the **learning curve** for divergence between training loss and validation loss, we can distinguish overfitting, underfitting, and good fit.
%[text] - In small-scale data (100-300 molecules), linear models often match or exceed NN performance; complex models should be introduced only when data volume and evidence of non-linearity are sufficient. \
%[text] **Linear Regression vs Neural Network  -- Criteria for Use**
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Aspect | Linear Regression | Neural Network |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | Data Scale | Small to Medium (N \< 1000) | Large (N \> 1000 recommended) |
%[text] | Interpretability | High (explainable by coefficients) | Low (black box) |
%[text] | Overfitting Risk | Low | High (requires regularization) |
%[text] | Non-linearity | Requires manual feature design | Learns automatically |
%[text] | Computational Cost | Low | High |
%[text:table]
%[text] 

